How to Argo

In this post, I will explain how to build proper Argo workflows together with Argo events. From workflow in workflow to outputs and containerSet

What is Argo?

Argo is an open source native framework for building products on Kubernetes. There are essentially four products. These are Argo Workflows, Argo CD, Argo Rollouts, and Argo Events. Altogether they have over 25.000 stars on GitHub. In this blog post, we will tackle Argo Workflows in depth and we will touch Argo Events

Argo Workflows

This is almost the direct competition of Apache Airflow and all of the other workflow schedulers out there. It allows us to build workflows based on yaml specification, resulting in Kubernetes pods being created on a Kubernetes Cluster.

You will see repeatedly the word WorkflowTemplate, Workflow, and Sensors, so I will explain it upfront. As a developer, you know classes and objects right? So WorkflowTemplate is a class and Workflow is the instance of the class (the living object at execution time). Sensors are basically listing events and triggering the correct workflow based on some rules. More of this later.

Here is an example how looks like:

Argo Workflows supports the following features:

  • Define workflows where each step in the workflow is a container.
  • Model multi-step workflows as a sequence of tasks or capture the dependencies between tasks using a graph (DAG).
  • Easily run compute-intensive jobs for machine learning or data processing in a fraction of the time using Argo Workflows on Kubernetes.
  • Run CI/CD pipelines natively on Kubernetes without configuring complex software development products.

Argo Events

Argo Events allows you to trigger workflows based on an event using a Sensor. We are using it to read messages from Kafka and start the correct pipeline with the proper parameters parsed from the payload.

Argo Events supports the following features:

  • Supports events from 20+ event sources.
  • Ability to customize business-level constraint logic for workflow automation.
  • Manage everything from simple, linear, real-time to complex, multi-source events.
  • Supports Kubernetes Objects, Argo Workflows, AWS Lambda, Serverless, etc. as triggers.
  • CloudEvents compliant.

Argo Installation

Argo has actually a very small fingerprint on the Kubernetes cluster. This is not normal for most schedulers. You can run Argo with 500MB of memory. Try to run Airflow, Airbyte or dagster at scale with 500MB, good luck. The installation is You can install it via helm and you can find it here with the following installation guide: https://argoproj.github.io/argo-workflows/quick-start/#install-argo-workflows

Implementation

In my implementation, I split this workflow into two. One is the “pipelineofstep” and the main workflow is our “pipelineof3”. I had to change the workflow a little bit so do not copy and paste this workflow.

Let’s see how a general implementation of the inner pipeline can look like.

Uhhh 200 lines of code to run this pipeline? Yes, this is how Argo works as it has the Kubernetes definitions as background. “pipelineofstep” is a template for file-1 and file-2 from our requirements. Now let’s try to go over the template and highlight the important parts.

  • We are using a DAG and not steps. (Line 13)
  • The DAG template actually receives inputs parameters and not the workflow itself. This is important when you call the workflow with argo sensors. (Line 26)
  • The DAG template returns outputs something (Line 30)
  • We are using containers and are chaining them together. (Example Lines 102, 108, 114)
  • The last container in the block if you have outputs or artifacts should be named main. (Line 69 and 128)
  • You can use jsonpath to extract values from a json input. (Line 68)

FAQ on Argo

How to abstract the version of the container that you are running?

On your step pass in a value from a Kubernetes configmap. See Line 69 from pipelineof3

How to call other workflows inside of my workflow?

See templateRef on Line 22 from pipelineof3. Check how we pass arguments into the inner workflow

How to propagate output information from A to C?

Use dag dependencies. See line 55 from pipelineof3

How to store general configurations over multiple workflows?

Kubernetes configmaps. Or you pass them as key into the arguments of your template or if you need a config into /etc/ just use Kubernetes volumes

How to store data between steps?

There is not much to handle here. You need to use Argo artifacts and hook them to S3 for example.

How to perform Monitoring?

This is a little bit hidden. On your workflow spec righ on the level from workflowMetadata you add a prometheus metric. See a full explanation on https://argoproj.github.io/argo-workflows/metrics/ 
Tipp: Extract this to workflowDefaults on argo deployment that you will have it to all workflows ;)

How to perform post operations like in a Jenkins pipeline?

On the docs you will find LifecycleHook. For me they don't work, tried on multiple K8 clusters and Argo versions (inclusive 3.4.0)
I found this bug: https://github.com/argoproj/argo-workflows/issues/9640 The workaround which works currently is to use onExit function.

How to generate workflows without YAML?

You can use python to generate the workflows and get rid of the repeated steps. Should I write a post about it ? Let me know in the comments

How to run multiple containers in one pod and share the data?

You need to use containerSet. You can define dependencies the same way as on a dag level. See pipelineofstep line 86. There are some cavets about it, all the containers start at the same time this is important to know because of resources. Let's say you have containers A and B in the same pod and you need 1GB of ram per container. This means your pod will only be schedule on a K8 node if you have 2 GB of ram. 
How I work around this is to set the requests for each container very small and the limit relative high. Then with the dependencies I kind of control which container uses which memory.

How to run small snippets of code inside of yaml?

Yes, you can have a template step like this:

How to scale a workflow?

This goes very on hand how you trigger the flows. In our case we use argo sensors but you could also use the API from argo to start the workflows. See also https://argoproj.github.io/argo-workflows/running-at-massive-scale/

How to have a sidecar container

Yes we are using a sidecar container because of the architecture from our product. That's why we have on all the steps from our pipeline wait-for-side-car container. It basicly just wait's until the port is available. See line 221 on pipelineof3

If you made it here then you are really interested in Argo. Feel free to make comments or if your company is looking into using Argo our company can help. Check out Datamesh GmbH for more information.

There is a missing piece on how to connect Argo workflows to Argo sensors. If you think this would be an interesting topic for a post, then let me know in the comment section

Overall Argo is great, but it still involves a lot YAML code which you cannot test against it. When things get complicated or long I prefer to have some unit tests. Currently, we only use Argo linting in our ci pipelines, but we are working on a way to use Python for the workflow definition. One of my next posts will cover this so stay tuned. pipelines.
